<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="7a877e72-4a08-5df1-86b3-5a6bc0184c4b" activityNameId="56f4de80-026b-5084-addf-2540a2c8fb00" parentActivityId="93392613-806e-5caa-8a24-6ababf59af31" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">flax straw production, dew-retted</activityName>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity begins with the destruction (green manure) of intermediate crop and preparation of land for sowing.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with the harvesting of the flax straw, dew-retted plant that is ready to be processed into the scutching process. Transport from field to scutching is excluded.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The data refer to fibre flax cultivation and retting in Western Europe (France, Belgium and the Netherlands), the 1st step to produce European Flax™ fibre. European Flax™ is a certification of origin and traceability owned by the Alliance for European Flax-Linen and Hemp (formerly known as CELC) which covers 100% of the fibres obtained from western European retted flax plants, and guarantees third party verified traceability downstream. The unit is 1kg of flax straw, dew-retted in 2014-2028 through Flax cultivation, retting and harvesting. Cultivation is modelled after the average common technical itinerary in the 3 countries including crop rotation; absence of irrigation (flax fields are not irrigated in western Europe, barring exceptional circumstances); reasoned use of fertiliser and pesticide; and 100% dew retting. It is 100% specific of Western Europe and cannot be used to represent any other geography. The detailed technical itinerary is available from the Alliance. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The process starts with the intermediate crop sown before flax in the Autum. It then includes preparing the field for sowing, sowing, inputs. Then flax is pulled and laid evenly in the field (around early July depending on weather) , where it will ret over the course of the next 3-7 weeks, depending on climatic conditions. During retting, microorganisms from the soil develop on the plants thanks to dew, rain and wind, leading to partial decomposition of the stem pectins that is key for flax quality. To achieve optimal retting, flax is turned midway through retting, and then finally, the retted stems are baled. The average yield is 6572.66 kg retted plant per ha. Application of fertilizers is included with N, P, K 168 kg-ha, the total N uptake is considered to be 72 kg/ha, only partially reintegrated with N fertilization, the remaining is from previous crop residues and organic matter mineralization. Transport from field to scutching is not included. This dataset has been modelled with the same activity data as the European Flax™ dataset in the Environmental Footprint 3.1 official database (data from the Alliance for European Flax-Linen &amp; Hemp), however LCIA results are slightly different for some indicators, mainly due to different background datasets used.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="8f4689ed-c3b8-436e-bb91-364624d93144">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">0116:Growing of fibre crops</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0723d252-7e2a-11de-9820-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RER</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The data represent a weighted average across the 3 European countries producing flax:  France, Belgium and the Netherlands.  This production is 100% certified to European Flax™ and represents 3/4 of the global production for flax long fibre.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The data refer to the average agricultural technical itinerary for the geography given.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2013-10-01" endDate="2023-09-30" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The data refer to 5 croping cycles from 2014 harvest until and including 2018 harvest .</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
    <flowData>
